Observations¶

  1. On an average, there are 3000 applications received in the US universities in which over 2000 applications are accepted and 780 new students are enrolled.
  2. The standard deviation is very high for variables apps, accept, and enrolled.
  3. The average expenses for room, books, and personal are 4357, 549, and 1340 respectively.
  4. The average fulltime undergrad students are 3699 which is higher than the average part time undergrad students.
  5. PhD and Grad Rate have maximum values greater than 100 which is unrealistic.

#Principal Component Analysis 

#defining number of principal components to generate
n = data_scaled.shape[1]

#finding principal components for the data 
pca = PCA(n_components=n, random_state=1)

data_pca1 = pd.DataFrame(pca.fit_transform(data_scaled))

#the percentage of variance explained by each principal component 
exp_var = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
In [15]:
#plotting cumulative variance by principal components 
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))

plt.plot(range(1,18),pca.explained_variance_ratio_.cumsum(),marker='o',linestyle='--')

plt.title("Explained variances by component")
plt.xlabel("Number of components")
plt.ylabel("Cumulative explained variance")

plt.show()
In [16]:
#finding the least number of components that can explain more than 70% variance 
sum = 0 


for ix, i in enumerate(exp_var):
    
    sum = sum+i 
    
    if(sum>0.70):
        
        print("Number of PCs that explain at least 70% variance:", ix+1)
        break
        

Number of PCs that explain at least 70% variance: 4

Observations¶

  1. As we can see, we reduced the number of features from 17 to 4 principal components. The first four principal components explain appropriately 70% of the original value.
  2. So that is about 76% reduction in the dimensionality of the dataset with only a loss of 30% in variance

Let's look at these principal components as a linear combination of the original features

Observations¶

  1. The first principal component, PC1 seems to be related to high values of student scores top10perc, top25perc, number of outstate students, the faculty education level, and instructional expenditure per student. The first principal component seems to capture the generally define premier colleges with a high quality of students entering them, and more accomplished faculty teaching there. The students entering these colleges also appear to be financially well-off.

  2. The second principal component, PC2 seems to be related to high values of number of applications received, accepted, and enrolled, and the number of full-time and part-time undergrad students. The second principal component seems to capture attributes that generally define non-premier colleges that are comparatively easier to get admissions into.

  3. The third principal component seems to be related to financial aspects i.e. personal spending and cost of books for individual students. It is also associated with low values of student faculty ratio.

  4. The fourth principal component seems to capture attributes that define colleges which lack highly educated faculty PhD and terminal and are comparatively easier to graduate from.

data_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(data_scaled)

data_tsne = pd.DataFrame(data_tsne, columns = ['X1', 'X2', 'X3'])

#scatter plot for all three components 
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (10,10))

ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection = '3d')

x = data_tsne['X1']

y = data_tsne['X2']

z = data_tsne['X3']

ax.scatter(x,y,z)

plt.show()

Observations¶

  1. t-SNE preserves the local structure of the data while embedding the data from high dimensions to low dimensions

  2. Here, we generated the 2D and 3D embeddings for the data. We can see that there is no pattern in the data. It is scattered and clustered together with the exception of some outliers.

  3. Let's try different perplexity values to visualize data in 2D

In [29]:
for i in range(10, 50, 5):
    tsne = TSNE(n_components = 2, random_state = 1, perplexity = i)
    
    data_tsne = tsne.fit_transform(data_scaled)
    
    data_tsne = pd.DataFrame(data_tsne)
    
    data_tsne.columns = ['X1', 'X2']
    
    plt.figure(figsize = (7, 7))
    
    sns.scatterplot(x = 'X1', y = 'X2', data = data_tsne)
    
    plt.title("perplexity = {}".format(i))

Observations¶

  1. All the plots with different perplexity values imply that there is no underlying pattern in the data.
  2. It shows that observing patterns in data projection and visualization techniques like PCA and SNE, is actually dependent on the nature of the data.
